The paper deals with the problem of finding compatible triangulations with a minimum number of Steiner points, which is a fundamental problem in computational geometry. The problem involves the representation and manipulation of geometric objects, which falls under the category of computational geometry (cs.CG). The use of Steiner points suggests that the paper may also involve data structures (cs.DS) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The problem of finding compatible triangulations can also be viewed as a combinatorial optimization problem, which falls under the category of computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the paper may also involve graph theory (cs.GT) since compatible triangulations provide piecewise linear homeomorphisms and are a crucial first step in morphing planar graph drawings.
